<DOC><DOCNO> AP900205-0101 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-02-05-90 1450EST</FILEID><FIRST>r w AM-US-Angola     02-05 0122</FIRST><SECOND>AM-US-Angola,110</SECOND><HEAD>US Urges Angola To Halt Military Offensive</HEAD><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   The State Department urged the Angolangovernment Monday to halt its military offensive againstU.S.-backed rebel forces and open negotiations on ending theconflict.   The military attempts to crush the UNITA rebels ``are futile andmake it increasingly difficult to reach the negotiated settlementnecessary to conclude this tragic conflict,'' said departmentspokeswoman Margaret Tutwiler.   She reaffirmed Washington's willingness to assist the warringfactions and the chief outside mediator, Zaire President MobutuSese Seko, in a search for peace.   The heaviest fighting has been around the rebel-held town ofMavinga, where Ms. Tutwiler said government air strikes arecontinuing.   The leftist government's main foreign supporter is the SovietUnion.</TEXT></DOC>